  "text": "The magnitude of daytime emissions also depends on the rate of methanol production within the plant. As mentioned in the introduction, the production is associated with the growth of plants, [CITATION_1] distinguished two classes of low and high methanol emitter species. In particular graminoids of the family poaceae, among them the main forage grass species, are low methanol emitters while most other plants belong to the high emitters (Galbally and Kirstine, 2002 and references therein) . In this study, the intensive field was mainly composed of graminoids of the family poaceae (85%), whereas the extensive field was composed of graminoids (35%), legumes (60%), and forbs (5%). This difference in the species composition may explain the generally higher emissions by the extensive field.",
